        Air Conditioning and HVAC When Selling a Brisbane Home
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Air conditioning is no longer a feature in Brisbane property. It is an expectation. Here is what buyers actually value, what to install before listing, and how to handle an older system without overcapitalising.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Air conditioning has shifted in Brisbane from a nice-to-have to a baseline expectation. Buyers inspecting homes in the $900,000 and up range in the inner east now assume that the main living areas and the principal bedrooms will be conditioned. If they walk into a home without it, they are not dismissing the property, but they are doing the mental arithmetic on what retrofitting will cost, and that number comes straight off their offer.</p>

      <p>At the same time, air conditioning is an area where it is easy to overspend in the lead-up to a sale. A full ducted retrofit on a character Queenslander can land between $12,000 and $22,000 installed, and buyers rarely return that cost in the offer price. The right approach is usually tighter and smarter: match the system to what buyers in your price bracket expect, make sure what is installed works reliably, and present it well.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What Brisbane buyers actually expect by price bracket</h2>
      <p>Expectations scale with price, and understanding where your home sits on that curve drives every decision from here.</p>

      <p>Up to around $900,000, buyers are looking for at least one reliable split system in the main living area. A second split in the principal bedroom is a significant plus. Anything beyond that is a bonus rather than a requirement.</p>

      <p>Between $900,000 and $1.5 million, the base expectation is a split in the living area, a split in the principal bedroom, and some form of cooling in the secondary bedrooms, whether ceiling fans with night breezes or additional splits. Homes at this price without any conditioning in the living area feel dated, regardless of other renovations.</p>

      <p>Above $1.5 million, buyers increasingly expect a ducted system or a comprehensive multi-split arrangement that covers every primary room. In the $2 million plus bracket, a zoned ducted system is close to a given. The absence of whole-home climate control at this price becomes something the agent has to explain away.</p>

      <p>These are not hard rules. A well-renovated character home with period detailing and two high-quality splits can outperform a flat-ceilinged post-war box with full ducting. But the price bracket sets the buyer's starting expectation, and the system needs to either meet it or obviously compensate for it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to install before selling, and when to leave it</h2>
      <p>The decision to install new air conditioning before listing turns on three things. First, what is currently installed. Second, the gap between what is installed and what the price bracket expects. Third, the time available before the campaign launches.</p>

      <p>If the home has no air conditioning at all and sits in the $900,000 plus bracket, installing a single high-quality split in the main living area is almost always a sound investment. Expect to spend $2,500 to $4,500 for a mid-to-large capacity wall split installed professionally, and expect buyers to read the space as a properly conditioned living area rather than one with a retrofit obligation attached. This is the single highest-return HVAC decision a seller can make.</p>

      <p>If the home has a living-area split and no bedroom cooling, and sits above $1 million, adding a second split to the principal bedroom is usually worthwhile. The cost is similar to the first install, and buyers strongly prefer a climate-controlled bedroom in Brisbane's humid months.</p>

      <p>If the home has splits across the main spaces but no ducted system, and sits above $1.8 million, the decision gets harder. Retrofitting ducting into a character home is expensive, disruptive, and rarely finishes on time for a listing. Unless the home has at least six months of lead time and a clear path for the ducts through the ceiling void, retaining and presenting the existing splits well is usually the better call.</p>

      <p>If the home already has a full ducted system that is more than twelve years old, test it thoroughly. A system that works but struggles to hold a set temperature on a hot day is a risk for the campaign. A service and refrigerant top-up can often resolve mid-life performance issues for $300 to $600, and is almost always worth doing before the first open home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Split systems: what buyers notice</h2>
      <p>Buyers register three things about a split system before they ever turn it on. The age and appearance of the indoor head. The tidiness of the pipework and the outdoor unit. And the capacity relative to the size of the room.</p>

      <p>An indoor head that is more than ten years old, yellowed from age, and browned along the filter grille is a visual liability regardless of whether it still works. Replacing a tired indoor head with a clean modern unit costs roughly the same as servicing the old one and dramatically improves the perceived quality of the cooling system. The same is true for outdoor units that have rusted, faded, or been positioned in an ugly location visible from the back garden.</p>

      <p>Pipework is the tell that separates a professional install from a rushed one. Neat ducted chase covers or painted pipe trays signal that the install was done properly. Exposed copper pipe in a tangle down the side of the house signals the opposite, and buyers will form a view on the rest of the property's maintenance from that detail. Tidying up exposed pipework or installing a simple chase cover is inexpensive and worth the effort.</p>

      <p>Capacity matters because an undersized system that cannot cool the room at forty degrees will not be remembered fondly by a buyer who inspects on a hot day. A 2.5 kilowatt unit trying to cool a forty-square-metre open-plan living area is a waste of the installation. If you are retrofitting before sale, size the unit correctly for the room. A good installer will advise, or ask them to size on the high side of the range rather than the low side.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Ducted systems: the common issues to pre-empt</h2>
      <p>Ducted systems that are ten years old or older are the area where pre-sale servicing consistently pays back. Five specific issues are worth checking before the property lists.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Refrigerant levels.</strong> A refrigerant top-up can restore a system that is no longer reaching its set temperature to full capacity. The gas itself is not expensive, and the labour to check and charge a system is typically under $400.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Filter condition.</strong> Grey, dust-caked return air filters are a visible signal of neglect. Replace them the week before photography and the week before the first open home.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Duct integrity.</strong> Flexible ducting in the roof void can split, separate at joins, or collapse over time. A technician inspection can identify issues that are halving system efficiency, and repairs are usually in the low hundreds of dollars.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Zone motor operation.</strong> Zoning motors fail quietly. A system that is supposed to zone four rooms but is actually cooling all four at once looks the same to the user but costs dramatically more to run. Have each zone tested individually.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Controller age.</strong> A wall controller that is scuffed, cracked, or running an old interface dates the whole system. A replacement controller is usually under $400 installed and signals a modern HVAC setup at a glance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Ceiling fans and night-breeze strategies</h2>
      <p>Ceiling fans are a useful complement to air conditioning, not a substitute for it at the Brisbane inner-east price bracket. Well-placed quiet DC fans in every bedroom and the main living area give buyers the sense that the home has been designed for the climate rather than relying on energy-intensive cooling alone. DC fans are close to silent at low speeds, which matters in bedrooms, and they photograph better than older AC-motor fans with exposed cowlings.</p>

      <p>In older Queenslanders with high ceilings, large openable windows, and good cross-ventilation, presenting the home's passive cooling is a genuine value point. Agents who can point out that the living area runs cool with the doors open on a north-easterly afternoon are telling buyers the home does not need to run climate control constantly. That is a running-cost story that resonates, particularly with buyers who have been paying attention to electricity prices.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solar and running cost disclosure</h2>
      <p>Running costs are increasingly part of how buyers evaluate a home, and HVAC is the single largest energy draw in most Brisbane properties. If the home has solar that reliably offsets summer cooling, make that concrete. The last three electricity bills, printed and available at the open home, are more persuasive than any verbal claim.</p>

      <p>If the home has a modern high-efficiency system or an inverter ducted unit, note the star rating. A 5-star or better ducted system running on solar gives buyers a concrete running cost picture that is genuinely reassuring at the price point.</p>

      <p>If the home has an older system with known high running costs, be honest about it rather than attempting to obscure the issue. Buyers will ask, and an evasive answer creates more doubt than a candid one. A more useful approach is to acknowledge the age of the system and leave room in the offer for the buyer to retrofit if they choose.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting HVAC through the campaign</h2>
      <p>Turn every split system and the ducted system on about thirty minutes before each open home, set to a comfortable twenty-three or twenty-four degrees. Buyers who walk into a conditioned home in a Brisbane summer form an emotional reaction to the comfort before they register anything else. That reaction is worth more than any staging detail.</p>

      <p>Clean the outdoor units before photography. Wipe down indoor heads. Replace filters. If you have paperwork for a recent service or a refrigerant top-up, keep it in a folder on the kitchen bench for buyers to see alongside compliance certificates, recent bills, and any warranties that transfer.</p>

      <p>For ducted systems, a simple printed page listing the brand, model, age, zoning layout, and most recent service date is a useful reassurance for buyers. It removes the vague unease buyers feel about inheriting an HVAC unknown, and it is the kind of detail that distinguishes a well-prepared vendor from an average one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When not to retrofit</h2>
      <p>There are a few situations where a pre-sale HVAC install is not worth the money. Homes where retrofitting would require structural alterations that cannot be finished before listing. Homes priced at entry-level brackets where even a single split is unlikely to return its cost. Homes in poor overall condition where HVAC would stand out as the one improved feature against a tired backdrop. And homes being marketed to developers or knock-down buyers, where fittings will be removed regardless.</p>

      <p>In those cases, leaving the HVAC decision to the purchaser is the cleaner call. Price the home appropriately for the absence, disclose the position clearly, and let the buyer weigh the cost themselves. A well-priced property without air conditioning will still sell in Brisbane's inner east. A poorly priced one with brand-new air conditioning installed in a rush will not.</p>

